WEBVTT

00:00:00.000 --> 00:00:06.040
So today, I'm going to be talking about a trial that just opened through our SWOG

00:00:06.040 --> 00:00:12.860
clinical trials partnership. It's called LUKE-01. And this is a phase two trial of

00:00:12.860 --> 00:00:19.020
blenitumumab, dasatinib, prednisone, and blenitumumab in patients with Philadelphia

00:00:19.020 --> 00:00:27.560
chromosome positive ALL. So just as some background, Philadelphia positive ALL is

00:00:27.560 --> 00:00:33.200
characterized by the Philadelphia chromosome. And we see this actually more commonly in about

00:00:33.200 --> 00:00:40.600
50% of patients that are greater than 50 years of age. And so this is relevant because it tends

00:00:40.600 --> 00:00:47.380
to be an older patient population with more comorbidities. Historically, this was associated

00:00:47.380 --> 00:00:53.640
with a very poor prognosis. And really, the only curative treatment option was allogeneic transplant.

00:00:54.120 --> 00:00:56.960
But things have now changed significantly.

00:00:57.560 --> 00:01:02.260
With the incorporation of TKIs, as well as now with blenitumumab.

00:01:03.500 --> 00:01:11.760
So some initial data that was done by Dr. Foa and colleagues, they looked at TKI and steroids.

00:01:13.200 --> 00:01:18.200
And the response rates with dasatinib and prednisone were extremely high,

00:01:18.200 --> 00:01:25.560
a 93% complete remission rate by complete hematologic response by day 22.

00:01:26.480 --> 00:01:27.480
The main issue was...

00:01:27.560 --> 00:01:33.900
The main issue was with just this approach, the disease-free survival at 20 months was only about

00:01:33.900 --> 00:01:41.440
51%. So these remissions were not very durable. They did show that MRD

00:01:41.440 --> 00:01:48.020
correlated with disease-free survival. And of the patients that relapsed, a significant number

00:01:48.020 --> 00:01:54.560
of patients had a T315I mutation that was in the B-serum abel kinase domain.

00:01:56.480 --> 00:02:04.220
So subsequently, there's now been nice work done by many groups looking at incorporating blenitumumab

00:02:04.220 --> 00:02:12.520
with TKI and steroids into frontline treatment. Blenitumumab is a bispecific T-cell engaging

00:02:12.520 --> 00:02:22.180
antibody that targets CD19. It was initially approved by the FDA for relapse refractory B-cell

00:02:22.180 --> 00:02:25.700
ALL, and then for MRD-positive ALL.

00:02:26.480 --> 00:02:35.720
And so this is data from two studies. One is the FOA study. In this study, they combined

00:02:35.720 --> 00:02:41.760
blenitumumab with dasatinib and steroids. They have now presented long-term follow-up.

00:02:42.380 --> 00:02:47.320
Their patient population was a younger patient population with a median age of 54.

00:02:48.320 --> 00:02:55.920
In their study, they did have about 24 out of 63 patients did undergo allogeneic transplant.

00:02:56.480 --> 00:03:03.020
So that may impact some of these results. And with a median follow-up of 53 months,

00:03:03.460 --> 00:03:09.460
they had very excellent disease-free overall and event-free survival. But again, in those

00:03:09.460 --> 00:03:13.200
patients that relapsed, they did see T315I mutations.

00:03:14.400 --> 00:03:22.940
Through SWOG, we conducted a study very similar, but this study was limited to patients 65 years

00:03:22.940 --> 00:03:24.320
of age and older. In this study, only one patient was able to get a T315I mutation.

00:03:24.320 --> 00:03:25.820
And so this study was limited to patients 65 years of age and older. In this study,

00:03:25.820 --> 00:03:26.300
only one patient was able to get a T315I mutation. And so this study was limited to patients 65 years of age and older. In this study, only one

00:03:26.300 --> 00:03:26.620
patient was able to get a T315I mutation. And so this study was limited to patients 65 years of age and older. In this study, only one

00:03:26.620 --> 00:03:32.780
patient actually underwent an allogeneic transplant. This median age here was 73 years.

00:03:33.580 --> 00:03:38.300
And the median follow-up we just presented at ASH this year was 5.6 years.

00:03:39.660 --> 00:03:43.260
And again, the results are not quite as good as FOA, but again, in an

00:03:43.260 --> 00:03:48.380
older patient population, and only one person undergoing transplant.

00:03:49.180 --> 00:03:56.120
And so the question is, can we improve upon these results? And particularly, can we try

00:03:56.120 --> 00:04:01.740
to decrease the risk of relapses with patients with T315I mutations?

00:04:02.760 --> 00:04:10.420
And so the MD Anderson group has done some very nice work looking at using panatinib with

00:04:10.420 --> 00:04:19.120
blenatumumab with excellent results and overall survival. The main issue has been that for some

00:04:19.120 --> 00:04:25.300
of our older patients with cardiovascular comorbidities, blenatumumab may be problematic.

00:04:25.640 --> 00:04:25.940
And so the question is, can we improve upon these results? And so the question is, can we try to

00:04:25.940 --> 00:04:28.320
improve upon these results? And so the question is, can we try to improve upon these results? And so the question is, can we try to get around this?

00:04:29.720 --> 00:04:40.800
And so a siminib is, it basically isn't able to directly, works differently than the other

00:04:40.800 --> 00:04:47.440
B-cerebral inhibitors, and has been shown to be active against T315I mutations.

00:04:48.400 --> 00:04:55.420
And so there's been data showing that this allosteric inhibitor or a siminib in combination

00:04:55.420 --> 00:05:03.640
with an ATP-competitive TKI may be able to deepen clinical responses and reduce the resistance of

00:05:03.640 --> 00:05:12.220
emergent mutations. And so this is the LUCA1 trial that we have currently just opened. It hasn't

00:05:12.220 --> 00:05:17.360
enrolled any patients yet. This is able to be opened through any SWOG sites.

00:05:18.220 --> 00:05:24.620
And basically, the regimen is very similar to the FOA regimen, but we're looking at a siminib

00:05:24.620 --> 00:05:34.140
and desatinib with steroids as induction. Patients then get post-remission treatment

00:05:34.140 --> 00:05:40.980
with a siminib and desatinib, followed by blenatumumab, desatinib, and then maintenance

00:05:40.980 --> 00:05:48.040
with a siminib, desatinib, and prednisone. And so the primary objectives are to assess

00:05:48.040 --> 00:05:55.480
the rate of major molecular remission by PCR. Cecilia Yung and Jerry Radich are also going to

00:05:55.480 --> 00:06:00.860
do some nice correlative work in their lab, evaluating and describing genes and pathways

00:06:00.860 --> 00:06:06.180
that are associated with response to therapy, as well as really looking at the spectrum of

00:06:06.180 --> 00:06:10.340
mutations that we observe and the timing of resistance.

00:06:11.920 --> 00:06:17.600
And so in conclusion, outcomes have really improved significantly, and most patients are now

00:06:17.860 --> 00:06:24.140
receiving blenatumumab with TKI therapy. I think we really are going to need longer follow-up to

00:06:24.140 --> 00:06:31.180
assess these outcomes, or follow-up even on these studies is still short. So the challenges that

00:06:31.180 --> 00:06:36.260
remain, I think I still struggle if you have a very young patient that's in their 20s and 30s.

00:06:36.680 --> 00:06:42.240
Most of us are doing blenatumumab and TKI, but I think we don't know what's going to happen

00:06:42.240 --> 00:06:47.460
20 and 30 years down the road. We, I think, need to learn how to prevent,

00:06:47.680 --> 00:06:55.380
and treat these resistant mutations. And also, one area that we've seen presented by both MD

00:06:55.380 --> 00:07:00.160
Anderson and other groups has really been now that we're starting, in some of these higher-risk

00:07:00.160 --> 00:07:08.140
patients, we're starting to see CNS relapse, or CNS disease. And so how do we help with this?
